{"id":"fa9d6f57-77e8-44fc-89fe-09107fe9edbe","title":"1497/11/09: footnote 3, p. 127-128","type":"main-list-block","children":[{"id":"46fc8b46-f65d-48d6-be56-3a1529c72879","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"This was opened in the year 1348, the moment that the plague was over, and obtained from Pope Clement VI. the privilege of conferring degrees; but it never became one of the large universities, partly because the expense seemed too great to many of the\u00A0citizens, and partly because art appealed more than science to this mobile city. Boccaccio commented here on Dante. It flourished mostly in 1421. Niccol\u00F2 da Uzzano left the greater part of his fortune to found a college in connection with it; but jealousy prevented his behest being carried out. The street in which stood the house intended for this purpose took the name of Sapienza; and the house was bought by Savonarola for San Marco to use for schools. [Trans.] The Studio had removed to Prato in consequence of the rebellion of Pisa. Parenti, who was one of the directors, wrote that it was now (in 1497) taking refuge in Florence, \u0022the plague being at Prato, and the Pistolese and the Aretini quarrelling as to which of them should have it.\u0022","standoffProperties":[{"id":"546b7faa-e090-4f3b-9c98-55f803dec21e","type":"page","start":0,"end":252,"value":"127","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"bcaab7af-4884-4011-be0c-401000b2fe41","type":"codex/time-reference","start":28,"end":31,"value":"53988bce-9cb7-4cfa-88c2-f393668c55b9","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"41946a23-acca-47d7-99e4-671a7520ea13","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":89,"end":103,"value":"2381fbdc-bd9f-4108-b0f3-f2cb28098d70","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"55312927-4c09-412e-bae2-7fd7a6fa1e85","type":"page","start":253,"end":1000,"value":"128","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"8b24b711-5d30-44d4-a306-1be60b9a3a3f","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":334,"end":342,"value":"1168d433-9530-41c6-a9cc-5dd6